{{Infobox journal | title = Cambridge Archaeological Journal | cover = Cambridge Archaeological Journal.jpg | image_size = 200px | editor = John Robb | discipline = | former_names = | abbreviation = Camb. Archaeol. J. | publisher = [[Cambridge University Press]] on behalf of the [[McDonald Institute for Archaeological Research]] | country = United Kingdom | frequency = Triannually | history = 1991-present | openaccess = | license = | impact = | impact-year = | website = http://journals.cambridge.org/action/displayJournal?jid=CAJ | link1 = http://journals.cambridge.org/action/displayIssue?jid=CAJ&tab=currentissue | link1-name = Online access | link2 = http://journals.cambridge.org/action/displayBackIssues?jid=CAJ | link2-name = Online archive | ISSN = 0959-7743 | LCCN = 91658653 }} The '''''Cambridge Archaeological Journal''''' is a [[Peer review|peer-reviewed]] [[academic journal]] for [[Cognitive archaeology|cognitive]] and symbolic [[archaeology]] published by [[Cambridge University Press]] on behalf of the [[McDonald Institute for Archaeological Research]].<ref name="Arq2001">{{cite book|title=Arq: architectural research quarterly|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8rtUAAAAMAAJ|accessdate=16 April 2011|year=2001|publisher=Emap Construct|page=189}}</ref> It was established in 1991 and is published triannually.<ref name="MI">{{cite web|url=http://www.mcdonald.cam.ac.uk/publications/caj/|title=Cambridge Archaeological Journal|publisher=McDonald Institute for Archaeological Research|accessdate=16 April 2011}}</ref> It includes major articles, shorter notes, book reviews,<ref name="Arq2000">{{cite book|author=Cambridge University Press. Online Journals|title=Arq: architectural research quarterly|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qLpUAAAAMAAJ|accessdate=16 April 2011|year=2000|publisher=Emap Construct}}</ref> and review articles, especially those related to cognitive archaeology.<ref name="GreeneMoore2010">{{cite book|last1=Greene|first1=Kevin|last2=Moore|first2=Tom|title=Archaeology: An Introduction|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qs6FSRx65JMC&pg=PA310|accessdate=16 April 2011|date=23 July 2010|publisher=Taylor & Francis|isbn=978-0-415-49638-4|pages=310–}}</ref>
The current [[editor-in-chief]] is [[John Robb (archaeologist)|John Robb]], ([[University of Cambridge]]),<ref name="Robb2007">{{cite book|last=Robb|first=John|title=The early Mediterranean village: agency, material culture, and social change in Neolithic Italy|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0HeNr9h56uEC&pg=PR1|accessdate=16 April 2011|year=2007|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-84241-9|page=i}}</ref> while from 1990-2005 the editor was [[Chris Scarre]] (McDonald Institute).<ref name="ScarreScarre2006">{{cite book|last1=Scarre|first1=Christopher|last2=Scarre|first2=Geoffrey|title=The ethics of archaeology: philosophical perspectives on archaeological practice|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-W-F_ifgYHYC&pg=PR7|accessdate=16 April 2011|year=2006|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-54942-4|page=vii}}</ref><ref name="dur.ac.uk">{{cite web|url=http://www.dur.ac.uk/archaeology/staff/?id=3296|title=Prof Chris Scarre, MA PhD FSA|date=April 16, 2011|publisher=Durham University|accessdate=16 April 2011}}</ref>
== Scope == The journal's focus is on the role and development of human intellectual abilities.<ref name="Association1991">{{cite book|author=British Archaeological Association|title=Journal of the British Archaeological Association|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=iRYpAAAAYAAJ|accessdate=16 April 2011|year=1991|publisher=British Archaeological Association.|page=152}}</ref> It covers theoretical and descriptive archaeological research, ranging from art and iconography, burial and ritual, representations and symbolism, to the evolution of human cognition.<ref name="MI"/><ref name="WilsonKeil2001">{{cite book|last1=Wilson|first1=Robert Andrew|last2=Keil|first2=Frank C.|title=The MIT encyclopedia of the cognitive sciences|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-wt1aZrGXLYC&pg=PA124|accessdate=16 April 2011|year=2001|publisher=MIT Press|isbn=978-0-262-73144-7|page=124}}</ref> The journal covers all eras and all areas,<ref name="Journals.cambridge.org">{{cite web|url=http://journals.cambridge.org/action/displayAbstract?fromPage=online&aid=676016&fulltextType=RA&fileId=S0959774307000030|title=Cambridge Archaeological Journal|publisher=Journals.cambridge.org|accessdate=16 April 2011}}</ref> from the Lower Palaeolithic to Colonialism, and from the Pacific to Central Asia.<ref name="MI"/> Of note, [[figurine]] studies have been widely discussed in several surveys, but in particular in its 1996 feature "Can We Interpret Figurines?".<ref name="PollockBernbeck2005">{{cite book|last1=Pollock|first1=Susan|last2=Bernbeck|first2=Reinhard|title=Archaeologies of the Middle East: critical perspectives|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Go3jR6_3MSIC&pg=PA155|accessdate=17 April 2011|year=2005|publisher=Wiley-Blackwell|isbn=978-0-631-23001-4|pages=155–}}</ref> The journal often publishes on [[Maya civilization |Maya]] archaeology.<ref name="McKillop2004">{{cite book|last=McKillop|first=Heather Irene|authorlink=Heather Irene McKillop|title=The ancient Maya: new perspectives|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BmPpbB2cXu4C&pg=PA14|accessdate=16 April 2011|year=2004|publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn=978-1-57607-696-5|pages=14–}}</ref>
